04337nam a2200541Ia 9781438462592DE-B159720240426104009.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240426t20162016nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97814384625927 a10.1515/97814384625922doi  a(DE-B1597)683172  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aTR659 7aPHO0010002bisacsh04a778.9400aAmerican Chartres :bBuffalo's Waterfront Grain Elevators. 1aAlbany : bSUNY Press, c[2016] 4cÂ©2016  a1 online resource (200 p.) :bTotal Illustrations: 167  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aExcelsior Editions00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tGrain, Power, Time -- tThe Elevators in this Book -- tPlates -- tCaptions -- tAcknowledgments -- tFurther Reading0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aOn a visit to Buffalo, New York, the French poet Dominique Fourcade was awed by the huge concrete grain elevators that line the city's river and lakefront. Turning to his guide, the poet Susan Howe, he exclaimed, "The American Chartres!" Taking Fourcade's exclamation as its title, Bruce Jackson's American Chartres documents Buffalo's surviving grain elevators, capturing these monumental buildings in all seasons and in various light; from the Buffalo River, the Ship Canal, and Lake Erie; from inside and from the top floors and roofs; in detail and in toto.Invented in Buffalo by Robert Dunbar and Joseph Dart, the city's first grain elevator went operational in 1843. By the mid-1850s, Buffalo was the world's largest grain port, and would remain so well into the twentieth century. Grain elevators made Buffalo rich, and they were largely responsible for the development of the Port of New York.While primarily functional objects, designed to move grain from one transportation modality to another, grain elevators are also beautiful structures, and they exerted a profound influence on many twentieth-century architects. Walter Gropius, one of the founders of the Bauhaus, collected photographs of American grain elevators and published two of Buffalo's elevators in 1913. The great Modernist architect Erich Mendelsohn came to Buffalo to photograph them in 1924, and they also influenced the practice of architects such as Le Corbusier and the Italian futurist Antonio Sant'Elia. More recently, the conceptual artists and photographers Bernd and Hilla Becher have included grain elevators in their documentation of industrial structures in Europe and North America.Despite their deep impact on twentieth-century architecture, Buffalo's grain elevators remained underappreciated. As they outlived their economic usefulness, many were destroyed. Only recently have local residents realized what treasures they are. Beautifully illustrated with more than 160 color photographs, this book documents what remains.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aArchitectural photography. 0aGrain elevatorszNew York (State)zBuffalovPictorial works. 4aFilm, Visual Culture, and Performing Arts : Art. 4aHistory : Architectural History/Architecture. 4aNew York/Regional : New York/Regional. 7aPhotography / Subjects & Themes / Architectural & Industrial.2bisacsh1 aJackson, Bruce, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package 2016z978311149098440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978143846259240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438462592423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438462592/original  a978-3-11-149098-4  SUNY Press eBook Package 2016b2016  aGBV-deGruyter-alles